Polymorphism:
-------------
Polymorphism is the ability of an object to take on many forms.

The most common use of polymorphism in OOP occurs when a parent class reference is used to refer to a child class object.
Parent p = new Child();
All Java objects are polymorphic since any object will pass the IS-A test for its own type and for the class Object.

Two things exist:

1️⃣ Reference Type → decides what methods you can call
2️⃣ Object Type → decides which overridden method runs

instanceof:
- checks the object type.
- depends on the actual object created using new, not the reference type.

Always ask:
What object was created with new? ignore reference type.

Then ask:
Is that object part of the hierarchy being checked? ---> to check instanceof

Types of Java Polymorphism:
---------------------------
1. Compile-time polymorphism is also known as static polymorphism and it is implemented by method overloading.
2. Run time polymorphism is also known as dynamic method dispatch and it is implemented by the method overriding.

The Golden Rule
----------------
Runtime polymorphism works ONLY for:

    ✔ Instance methods
    ❌ Static methods
    ❌ Private methods
    ❌ Final methods

Polymorphism allows:
👉 You can only call methods that exist in the reference type
👉 But overridden versions are chosen at runtime by JVM based on the actual object type created with new

It does NOT allow:
👉 Accessing child-specific methods using parent reference


Runtime polymorphism = Concept
Dynamic binding = Mechanism that makes it happen
dynamic binding enables runtime polymorphism.

@Override is not mandatory, but it is good practice because it helps the compiler detect errors in method overriding.